{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Traditional thermal comfort models, as described above, are developed based on aggregated data from a large population.",
    "So, rather than predicting the thermal comfort of individuals, they were designed to predict the average thermal comfort of a population, when all its members are exposed to the same environment.",
    "This naturally misses the inevitable and sometimes significant differences in how different individuals respond to the same thermal environment.",
    "A new approach to thermal comfort modeling that uses personal comfort models instead of the average response of a large population, can be applied to any building thermal control system (Kim et al., 2018).",
    "Personal thermal comfort can adapt to the available input variables, such as environmental variables (Cheung et al., 2017), occupant behaviors (Kim et al., 2018), and physiological signals (Liu et al., 2019)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "A new approach to thermal comfort modeling that uses personal comfort models instead of the average response of a large population, can be applied to any building thermal control system (Kim et al., 2018).",
    "Personal thermal comfort can adapt to the available input variables, such as environmental variables (Cheung et al., 2017), occupant behaviors (Kim et al., 2018), and physiological signals (Liu et al., 2019)."
